Bias Demo - sample mean & variance

This activity is a demo of sample statistics being (un)biased estimators of their population parameters. We will examine \(\overline{X}\) as an estimator for \(\mu\) and the sample variance \(s^2\) as an estimator for \(\sigma^2\).

Load packages

We first need to load the tidyverse, dslabs, and infer packages using the library() command.

library(tidyverse)
library(dslabs)
library(infer)

Prepare the data

We can load a dataset called gapminder that contains data on 185 countries from the years 1960 to 2016. We are going to consider the distribution of the variable life_expectancy.

data("gapminder", package = "dslabs")

Letâs first filter the data to keep only the year 2015.

gapminder_2015 <- gapminder %>% 
  filter(year == 2015)

gapminder_2015 has data on life expectancy for 185 countries. We will consider this to be our population. We can visualize the distribution of life_expectancy with a histogram.

ggplot(gapminder_2015, aes(x = life_expectancy)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "white", binwidth = 2) + 
  theme_minimal()

Population mean & Sample mean

We can compute the true mean \(\mu\) life expectancy in the population by:

gapminder_2015 %>% 
  summarize(n = n(),
            mu = sum(life_expectancy)/n)
    n       mu
1 185 72.21459

Suppose we donât have access to this population level data and instead only have data on a random sample of 5 countries. This means we donât know \(\mu\) but have to estimate it.

Letâs draw a random sample of size 5 and compute the sample mean.

sample <- gapminder_2015 %>% 
  sample_n(5)
sample
           country year infant_mortality life_expectancy fertility population
1        Sri Lanka 2015              8.4            77.6      2.31   20715010
2 Papua New Guinea 2015             44.5            60.9      3.67    7619321
3          Belgium 2015              3.3            80.5      1.86   11299192
4      Switzerland 2015              3.4            83.0      1.55    8298663
5         Suriname 2015             19.0            72.0      2.22     542975
  gdp continent         region
1  NA      Asia  Southern Asia
2  NA   Oceania      Melanesia
3  NA    Europe Western Europe
4  NA    Europe Western Europe
5  NA  Americas  South America
sample %>% 
  summarize(n = n(),
            xbar = mean(life_expectancy))
  n xbar
1 5 74.8

Recall that for an estimator to be unbiased, it doesnât mean each estimate âhits the targetâ (equals \(\mu\)) EVERY time, but that on average (in the long run) it hits the correct target (is centered around the correct value).

We can draw 10,000 random samples of size 5 and compute the sample mean in each sample with the following code:

means <- rep_sample_n(gapminder_2015, size = 5, reps = 10000) %>% 
  group_by(replicate) %>% 
  summarize(n = n(),
            xbar = sum(life_expectancy)/n)

We now have 10,000 \(\overline{X}\) estimates, from 10,000 different random samples. We can look at the distribution of these 10,000 values.

ggplot(means, aes(x = xbar)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "white") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = mean(gapminder_2015$life_expectancy), 
             color = "red") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = mean(means$xbar), 
             color = "blue", linetype = 2) +
  theme_light()
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

We can calculate \(E(\overline{X})\) (the long-run average of the sample mean).

means %>% 
  summarize(Exbar = mean(xbar))
# A tibble: 1 Ã 1
  Exbar
  <dbl>
1  72.3

Since the sample mean \(\overline{X}\) is an unbiased estimator of the population mean \(\mu\), we have \(E(\overline{X}) = \mu\).

Population variance and sample variance

Recall that we can compute the true variance \(\sigma^2\) of life expectancy in the population by:

gapminder_2015 %>% 
  summarize(sigma2 = var(life_expectancy))
    sigma2
1 60.69472

Suppose we donât have access to this population level data and instead only have data on a random sample of 5 countries. This means we donât know \(\sigma^2\) but have to estimate it. Letâs consider two possible ways to estimate \(\sigma^2\) from our sample data:

  1. \(s^2_n = \frac{\sum_{i = 1}^n (x_i - \overline{x})^2}{n}\)
  2. \(s^2 = \frac{\sum_{i = 1}^n (x_i - \overline{x})^2}{n-1}\)

Letâs draw a random sample of size 5 and compute these two estimates from our sample data.

sample <- gapminder_2015 %>% 
  sample_n(5)
sample
     country year infant_mortality life_expectancy fertility population gdp
1      Qatar 2015              6.8            79.7      1.98    2235355  NA
2 Mozambique 2015             56.7            57.1      5.04   27977863  NA
3      Japan 2015              2.0            83.2      1.45  126573481  NA
4     Poland 2015              4.5            77.6      1.44   38611794  NA
5   Colombia 2015             13.6            78.0      2.23   48228704  NA
  continent         region
1      Asia   Western Asia
2    Africa Eastern Africa
3      Asia   Eastern Asia
4    Europe Eastern Europe
5  Americas  South America
sample %>% 
  summarize(n = n(),
            xbar = sum(life_expectancy)/n,
            s2_n = sum((life_expectancy - mean(life_expectancy))^2) / n, 
            s2 = sum((life_expectancy - mean(life_expectancy))^2) / (n - 1))
  n  xbar    s2_n      s2
1 5 75.12 85.0856 106.357

Which one is a better estimate of \(\sigma^2\)? Remember that \(s^2_n\) and \(s^2\) are both random variables because they are functions of the random variables \(x_i\) (the life expectancy in the randomly selected country \(i\)). If we were to draw a different random sample, it might be the case that the other estimator gave us a âbetterâ estimate (closer to the true \(\sigma^2\)). In order to see which one is best in the long-run, letâs run 10,000 simulations, by taking 10,000 random samples and computing the two variance estimates in each.

variances <- rep_sample_n(gapminder_2015, size = 5, reps = 10000) %>% 
  group_by(replicate) %>% 
  summarize(n = n(),
            xbar = sum(life_expectancy)/n,
            s2_n = sum((life_expectancy - mean(life_expectancy))^2) / n, 
            s2 = sum((life_expectancy - mean(life_expectancy))^2) / (n - 1))

Letâs now compute the expected value (average) of each estimator.

variances %>% 
  summarize(Exbar = mean(xbar),
            Es2_n = mean(s2_n),
            Es2 = mean(s2))
# A tibble: 1 Ã 3
  Exbar Es2_n   Es2
  <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
1  72.2  48.7  60.9

Which one is closer to the true \(\sigma^2\) value?

As these results indicate, \(s^2_n = \frac{\sum_{i = 1}^n (x_i - \overline{x})^2}{n}\) is a biased estimator of \(\sigma^2\). In other words, itâs expected value is not equal to \(\sigma^2\); in the long-run, on average, it does not âhit the targetâ and estimate the correct value.

Dividing by \(n-1\), however, as in \(s^2 = \frac{\sum_{i = 1}^n (x_i - \overline{x})^2}{n - 1}\), gets rid of the bias and does âhit the correct targetâ. That is, \(E(s^2) = \sigma^2\).
